Hi folks,

I am seeing that this is a recurrent topic in Bootstrap discussions: #36170, #37877, #33488, #39512, in the `RTLCSS` repository: [#314](https://github.com/MohammadYounes/rtlcss/issues/314), [#301](https://github.com/MohammadYounes/rtlcss/issues/301) and even [on StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com/a/71746320/2035354). On both places it is mentioned one of the plugins that I maintain: [postcss-rtlcss](https://github.com/elchininet/postcss-rtlcss).

`postcss-rtlcss` does exactly this. It uses [RTLCSS](https://rtlcss.com/) behind the scenes to compile a CSS with both directions at the same time with the intention of changing the `dir` attribute of the HTML (or a specific class) and make the layout to change from LTR to RTL (or vice versa) without the necessity of loading an extra stylesheet.

Using `postcss-rtlcss` is not only an easy task to perform (just adding another plugin to the postcss config) but it also solves the third limitation mentioned [here](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/getting-started/rtl/#ltr-and-rtl-at-the-same-time) and it mitigates in a great level the second one, because it doesn‘t double the size of the CSS. Only declarations that are affected by direction are the ones that are prefixed. Comparing [bootstrap.min.css with both directions](https://github.com/elchininet/bootstrap-bidi/blob/5f5ec3f0341bfb9ba9aa5f6a1d1600e9e5c39cf7/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css) (280 KB) with [bootstrap.min.css with a single direction](https://github.com/twbs/bootstrap/blob/99562ba37c26aded816fa610210057518e13babb/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css) (227 KB) it can be noticed that the increment is a 23%.

On top of that, the proposed solution works overriding the LTR styles with the RTL ones, this will bring issues sooner or later because if a `left` declaration is overridden by a `right` one, the previous one should be cancelled, otherwise one will end up with both classes in RTL:

```css
.test {
    padding-left: 10px;
}

.rtl .test {
    padding-right: 10px;
}
```

In RTL `.test` will have padding `10px` on both sides, so [the previous padding-left should be cancelled](https://elchininet.github.io/postcss-rtlcss/#65e70db09f214).

But even doing that cancelling operation, overriding styles could bring multiple issues (this is mentioned in the README of `postcss-rtlcss` in [the section relative to override modes](https://github.com/elchininet/postcss-rtlcss#output-using-the-override-mode) in the subsection `Disadvantage of the override methods`). It is better to use [the combined mode](https://github.com/elchininet/postcss-rtlcss#output-using-the-combined-mode-default) with [the safeBothPrefix option](https://github.com/elchininet/postcss-rtlcss#safebothprefix) enabled to cover cases [in which the specificity of the prefixed rules could affect other rules that have been not flipped](https://elchininet.github.io/postcss-rtlcss/#65e710b8a8ca5).

I have built [the Bootstrap site using both directions](https://elchininet.github.io/bootstrap-bidi/) in `combined` mode with `safeBothPrefix` option enabled, and added a selector at the end of the header to switch between LTR and RTL and add the proper `dir` attribute to the HTML, so you can check what `postcss-rtlcss` does with a real life example.

Mentioning this in the [LTR and RTL at the same time](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/getting-started/rtl/#ltr-and-rtl-at-the-same-time) section will help a lot of users who are searching for the same and it will provide them with a better and more straightforward alternative.

Let me know if you find it valuable 🙂

Regards

